    oneLiner: "Natural theology is the branch of philosophy that investigates what can be known about God through reason alone, apart from divine revelation.",
    body: "Natural theology holds that certain truths about God—his existence, his unity, his intelligence, his goodness—can be known through the natural light of human reason, without recourse to Sacred Scripture or divine revelation. This is a foundational principle of Catholic intellectual life, affirmed by the First Vatican Council (1870), which taught that God can be known with certainty from created things by the natural light of reason (Dei Filius, ch. 2). The classical arguments for God's existence—from motion, efficient causality, contingency, degrees of perfection, and teleology (Aquinas's Five Ways), as well as the cosmological, moral, and teleological arguments in their modern forms—belong to natural theology. These truths are called the 'preambles of faith' (praeambula fidei) because they establish the rational credibility of belief in God as a preparation for receiving the supernatural gift of faith. Natural theology does not replace revelation but shows that faith is reasonable and that the God of the philosophers is the same God who reveals himself in Christ.",
