    body: "The claim that the Catholic Church is an enemy of learning is contradicted by the historical record. The Church preserved classical civilization through monastic scriptoria during the Dark Ages; invented the university system in the twelfth and thirteenth centuries (Paris, Bologna, Oxford, Cambridge); and produced towering intellects across every field: Augustine and Aquinas in philosophy and theology, Albertus Magnus in natural science, Roger Bacon in empirical method, Copernicus and Lemaitre in cosmology, Mendel in genetics, Lavoisier in chemistry, and Pasteur in microbiology. Jesuits alone have contributed to astronomy, linguistics, cartography, mathematics, and seismology. The Pontifical Academy of Sciences, founded in 1603, is one of the world's oldest scientific academies. Catholic social thought gave birth to the concept of human rights; Catholic canon law shaped Western legal traditions; Catholic aesthetics produced the Gothic cathedral, Gregorian chant, and the masterworks of Michelangelo, Dante, and Mozart. This tradition demonstrates that Catholic faith is not opposed to intellectual life but has consistently been its greatest stimulus.",
